title: Slidr
text:
Slidr
In today's world faced paced world, riddled with AI Tools and cheaper labour elsewhere, employees are expected to strive to become a ‘x10 engineer’ or perform at 200% percent efficiency to stay relevant and afloat. Hence, many have turned to AI to automate many mundane and cumbersome day-to-day tasks. Slide creation is prevalent in every workplace setting, at all levels. A good deck of slides seeks to efficiently communicate a message to a target audience. However, that is the only thing efficient about it. Significant thought and effort is required in each phase of the process: Structuring content, Design and Deliverance.

title: Slidr
text:
Slidr
Nowadays many automated tools have been created to fill this gap (such as: ). However, most are arguably sub-par, and usually only target a singular phase of the process. Creating a general  slide generation tool is incredibly challenging. This is due to the vast differences in presentations due to style (design, delivery) and context (audience, specific company requirements, etc).

title: Slidr
text:
Powerpoint Generator 
To address this issue, we decided to create a personalised slide generation tool. This tool should be able to adapt to the specific requirements of each user/company, account for different audiences, and address each phase of the slide creation process. It would be ideal (an absolute miracle) if we were able to create an end-to-end tool that delivered on all above requirements and produced perfect slides that require little to no edits. More realistically, we intend to create a tool that helps overcomes the initial inertia to slide creation, to create something personalised that employees can build upon, allowing them to focus on more important details in the presentation.

title: Slidr
text:
Slide Fitting vs Slide Generation 
After we started building the tool, we quickly realised it was extremely challenging to generate ‘good’ slides from text, even with a detailed prompt with appropriate context. Most AI tools function well when given a specific set of instructions and parameters to complete a sequential almost algorithmic task but fail spectacularly when it comes to open ended tasks that require creativity or more nuance, such as exploration or in this case design. 

To remedy, this we chose a different approach: Slide Fitting. In this approach, the user will upload a set of general pre-formatted slide templates (or choose from defaults we provide) and the tool will then decide which slide template is most appropriate for each part of the content and fit the content to the slide. Before you start frowning, hear me out. Disregarding the obvious disadvantage of having to manually create the initial deck of side templates, there are many benefits to this approach. For example, companies would be able to input specific templates that they require in all presentations, like a security classification on each slide, or a recommended standard presentation flow. This uniformity ensures coherence and standardisation across the board, allowing users to focus more on the message to be delivered. We acknowledge that this will not hold for ALL users, (i can already hear my friends from Figma __) but we believe that in places where the focus of presentations is to solely convey a message (rather than dazzle), this tool would be a great help.

text:
Slide Fitting vs Slide Generation 
(I also believe some of us {the less artistically inclined},  and our audience, may benefit from such an approach. Designers can design, and we can just reuse professionally designed slide template and focus on our delivered message.)

title: Slidr
text:
Layered Approach *structure as user benefit 
In our quest for personalisation, we took a layered approach to ensure maximal context awareness. This __ in three layers: 1. Content Generation 2. Slide Analysis 3. Slide & Script Generation.

title: Slidr
text:
Layered Approach *structure as user benefit 
The __ output of these tools is largely dependent on input, hence, we first guide our users to build a good prompt, by allowing them to set the required tone, target audience and most importantly provide any relevant documents pertaining to the presentation. With this context, we generate the content of the presentation, focused on structure and flow. Thereafter we section the content into different slides.

title: Slidr
text:
Layered Approach *structure as user benefit 
Secondly, we analyse the slide template provided, and identify what kind of content each slide might best represent. For example a slide with just a big header and a caption might be used as a title/ opening slide.

title: Slidr
text:
Layered Approach *structure as user benefit 
Thirdly, for each section, we then split the content into “to say” and “to show” categories. Thereafter, we pick the slide can best represent the “to show”content , and fit each part of the content to the slide. Finally, we take all the “to say” content and generate a script befitting of the audience, length of presentation and tone provided.

title: Slidr
text:
Conclusion * What I would improve with more time
Although our project sadly did not the hackathon (less take the world by storm), we strongly believe that this novel approach to slide generation makes the most logical sense and would be extremely beneficial to many.

General Background
I am a third-year Computer Engineering student at Nanyang Technological University in Singapore, currently on exchange at the University of California, Berkeley. I have completed several internships and am actively involved in college clubs and societies, where I enjoy working in dynamic, collaborative environments. I am deeply passionate about innovative technology—especially when it can be applied meaningfully to create positive real-world impact. Beyond academics and work, I enjoy staying active and creative. I play basketball, compete in varsity-level Taekwondo competitions, and am training as an aspiring triathlete. I also play electric bass in a band and have performed at several university events. I thrive in fast-paced, rigorous environments and am driven by curiosity, exploration, and new experiences.

My work focused on increasing computational efficiency by leveraging GPU-based systems, particularly through parallelising clustering algorithms on a HIP-based GPU architecture. I researched and implemented clustering techniques such as DBSCAN, HDBSCAN, and Mean-Shift, and benchmarked their performance using simulated datasets. This experience deepened my understanding of high-performance computing, parallel algorithms, and the practical challenges of deploying GPU-accelerated systems.

I conducted in-depth research across multiple areas of deep learning, including artificial neural networks, convolutional neural networks, generative AI, retrieval-augmented generation, and reinforcement learning. At NTU, I am part of REACH, an engineering club focused on developing assistive technologies for the differently abled in collaboration with organisations such as AWWA and MDAS. The club runs approximately seven active projects each academic year, and I am directly involved in two of them. My primary project aims to improve visual testing workflows in hospitals through an integrated hardware–software system. The software component is built in Python using PyQt6 for the graphical user interface and computer vision pipelines involving filtering, cascade thresholding, and vectorised operations for efficiency. The hardware component uses an Arduino interfaced with servo motors, lasers, and haptic and feedback devices such as buttons, buzzers, and lights, with real-time communication between hardware and software handled via serial communication.

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Context
Glaucoma is a chronic, progressive optic neuropathy and is the leading cause of irreversible blindness worldwide. Key to the management of glaucoma is the accurate and precise assessment of visual field (VF) function to detect VF loss from glaucoma and to monitor disease progression, which impacts important clinical decisions with respect to medication titration, laser procedures and even surgery. VF function is monitored commonly with automated perimetry; This utilises light stimulus and requires similar user interactions to evaluate the user’s VF.

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Problem 
The reliability of VF testing is critical in ensuring meaningful results which will accurately inform clinical management decisions. Reliability is often difficult to achieve, due to the initial learning curve for the patients, as well as variability in patient understanding and executing the test protocols. Current practices rely heavily on explanation and attention of the attending ophthalmic technician, and patient comprehension and cooperation – both of which may be highly variable, leading to unreliable results that can compromise the accuracy of disease monitoring. This undermines efforts to optimise treatment strategies tailored to individual patient needs.

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Problem 
In real-world clinical setting, appointment slots for VF testing are often limited by manpower and availability of testing devices. VF testing is a relatively time-consuming and tedious process, taking up to 10 minutes per patient, depending on the testing algorithm used. This does not include additional time required for equipment set up, patient transfer and explanation of testing process. Hence, when a patient’s VF test results are unreliable, resource constraints make it challenging to schedule a retest in close time proximity. This leads to an inefficient use of appointment slots for the clinic, and a missed opportunity to collect valuable data for the patient’s care. This would delay diagnosis or detection of disease progression.

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Problem Breakdown
To tackle this problem, we first spoke to ophthalmologists to identify the gaps in current practices. After extensive discussion, we broke the problem down into two parts: Instruction and Execution.

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Problem Breakdown
Instruction:

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Problem Breakdown
The patients in which these ophthalmologists have the most trouble with, are usually the elderly. With this group of people, struggles usually originate from a communicative breakdown. Due to the relative complexity of the test, significant time is spent on clarification. This problem is also exacerbated by potential language barriers and/or hearing impairments.

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Problem Breakdown
Execution:

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Problem Breakdown
Given the enclosed nature of the test and that results are not known until the end of the 10 minute long procedure, doctors or nurses would not be able to consistently track and correct any mistakes in execution. Hence, any misunderstandings, unconscious habits or errors will go unidentified and only be reflected in via a failed test.

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Problem Breakdown
Hence, we to sufficiently address both parts of the problem, we decided to 1. Create a simplified instructional video to relay information and 2. Make a pre-assessment simulation booth for patients to familiarise with test procedures and environment as well as nurses to identify any potential misunderstandings or errors.

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Problem Breakdown
This solution should provide standardised, user-friendly instruction for patients, accompanied by hands-on practical practice with immediate sensory or tactile feedback.

title: The Evolution of EyeTracker
text:
The Problem Breakdown
In totality, this aims to reduce the VF testing learning curve for patients and enhance patient education - thereby improving reliability and consistency of test outcomes.
